<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Icax Ltd (HOT15)</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Icax Ltd (HOT15)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ICAX </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Ltd </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is the innovative designer and installer of Interseasonal Heat Transfer. Interseasonal Heat Transfer integrates complementary renewable energy technologies to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> capture surplus solar energy in summer, store the heat in ThermalBanks over the autumn in order to release heat economically to buildings in winter. ICAX is leading the drive to provide Economic Renewable Energy.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This written evidence is submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Edwa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rd Thompson </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">who </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is a director of ICAX Ltd and is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the Treasurer of the Ground Source Heat Pump Association.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The response has been restricted to questions </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">relating to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> heat pumps</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the RHI</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and thermal storage</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">What will the local environmental impact </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(for example air pollution) be from the use heat generation in urban areas, for example CHP units?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is zero local environmental impact from the use of ground source heat pumps in urban areas (no emissions, no noise, no</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">visible impact</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as ground source</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> heat pumps pr</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ovide invisible heating systems</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">What are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This depends on the efficiency of the power station in c</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onverting gas to electricity (normally around 50%) and the Co-efficient of Performance </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(CoP) </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ground source</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> heat pumps (normally around 400%). If heat pumps </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are poorly installed there is a danger that the CoP could fall to 200% and, at that level, there would be no merit in using heat pumps. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ground source heat pumps can now be used in conjunction with solar thermal collection in summer and heat storage in gro</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">und arrays to yield COPs of over 500%. In these installations a clear advantage can be demonstrated for centralised electricity production plus domestic </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ground source </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">heat pumps.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ground source heat pumps in well insulated buildings can be set to provide ba</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ckground heating at night (when electricity supply is significantly cheaper).</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Why is community heating/CHP not more common in the UK?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Legal problems and custom have held back district heating schemes in the UK, as well as issues of measuring heat used b</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y customers of district heating. CHP has advantages in the heating season – but only marginal advantage in summer, unless connected to Seasonal Thermal Energy Storage.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Should the government take any further any specific actions in relation to cooling? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We know that DECC are opposed to the idea of subsidising cooling by air conditioning: we are very much in sympathy with the idea that standard air conditioning should not be encouraged – because there are large carbon emission implications. This is because</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the standard approach to cooling – heat </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">exchange with h</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ot air – is expensive in electricity [and therefore carbon emissions].  The CoP (</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Coefficient of Performance) of </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">roof-mounted </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">chiller can be as low as 1.5 on a hot day [1 kilowatt of electricity is n</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eeded to provide 1.5 kW of cooling].  However, some cooling is necessary, and there is a very much more effective way of achieving this – by employing ground source energy and </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">allowing </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">heat</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to escape to</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cold ground instead of forcing heat into hot air.  Th</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e CoP of “free cooling” (heat exchange with cold ground by means of a circulation pump) can be as high as 25. The CoP of Renewable Cooling (heat exchange with cold ground </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">assisted by</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a reversible heat pump) can frequently achieve a CoP of </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The carbon </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">emission savings of using Renewable Cooling, instead of standard Air Conditioning,</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are huge</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and we believe that DECC will come to see that these should be encouraged.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There will need to be appropriate safeguards, which could be defined in terms of requirin</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g a high CoP before Renewable Cooling is recognised and requiring a high temperature set point so that Cooling is only used when necessary (rather than as an indulgence).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DECC needs to acknowledge that a by-product of Renewable Cooling is to heat the groun</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d. The heat in the ground becomes a major asset when heating is required the following winter. Renewable Heating makes Renewable Cooling </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> efficient </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">and vice versa</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DECC ha</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">been </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inclined to reject </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">subsidy for renewable cooling as their interpretation o</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f the Renewable Energy Directive</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(RED)</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is that it would not count as “renewable”</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> although it would save significant CO2 emissions. We think that DECC, which frequently claims that the RHI is a “world first”,</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> should be making the case to Brusse</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ls, rather t</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">han follow</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DECC’s</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> own timid interpretation of the RED.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Why does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfully? </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The practical effect of DECC policy (although not the intention) has been to suppress the heat pump market</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and to drive some installers into insolvency</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Five years of discussion RHI, but no RHI yet in place for domestic heat pumps.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">FITs subsidies from </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">April 2010</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">diverted attention to PV cells, with initial subsidies </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">up to </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> p/kWhr</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> [when th</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e price of electricity was only </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">p/kWhr]</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Commercial RHI for heat pumps was introduced </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Nov</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ember </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2011, with initial subsidy at only 3.</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> p/kWhr (at the same time RHI for biomass introduced at 9</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.2</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> p/kWhr).</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DECC also introduced the unscientific idea of “na</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">turally occurring energy” which confused the market and prevented Ofgem from accrediting </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">any</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ground source heating and cooling systems</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">for over a year</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DECC have overlooked th</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ability of ground source heat pumps to provide invisible heating systems with zero on-site environmental impact.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ground source heat pumps can also recycle energy from summer to winter and, through thermal energy storage, they can balance the limitations o</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">other</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">renewable </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">technologies which suffer from intermittent energy supply.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The RHI provides an annual subsidy to reduce the annual cost of using renewable heat. The barrier to installing a ground source heat pump is not the annual running cost (which is </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">small) but the up-front capital cost (which is large).</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The RHI effectively aims to subsidise inefficient technologies over efficient ones. DECC argues that inefficient technologies need more subsidy to be employed. This discriminates against the use of eff</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">icient technologies like ground source heat pumps. This is the opposite of what DECC should be doing.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The RHI provides a subsidy to the owner of a building over many years if renewable heating is installed. The RHI provides no subsidy </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at all </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to the builder</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> who often decides which form of heating will be used (and </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">therefore</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> chooses the cheapest capital cost).</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">How successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> depend on the efficiency with which the RHI is administered by Ofgem. This, in turn, </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> depend on the complexity of the regulations Ofgem is asked to administer.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DECC has taken far too long to decide its approach and has a tendency to introduce impracti</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cal and confusing elements that will add to the cost of administration and present barriers to uptake.  The idea of using EPC certificates as the financial basis of administering the Domestic RHI is unhelpful. EPC certificates were introduced for other rea</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sons and DECC should not attempt to pass off responsibility in this way to estate agents who are not knowledgeable and are not disinterested parties.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We fear that there may be more people employed by Ofgem to administer the RHI than there will be people em</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ployed in the country to install ground source heat pumps.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Thermal storage is a potential useful method of balancing electricity/energy demand both diurnally and annually.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hermal storage using seasonal thermal energy storage is a simple and practical </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">method of balancing energy demand which is already in use in the UK. Government policy has not yet recognised the merits of this approach in saving carbon emissions</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The misconceived policy of “naturally occurring energy”</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> held back market developments in t</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">his </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">innovative </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">technology. DECC has</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> now</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recognised that this was inappropriate, but</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Statutory Instrument of 28 November 2011 has not yet been updated. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">What is government policy doing to promote thermal storage, and should it do more/different?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are not yet aware of any government policy to promote thermal storage – in spite of the power of thermal storage to reduce overall energy consumption and reduce greenhouse gas emissions significantly. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government policy urgently needs to recognise and p</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">romote </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Seasonal Thermal Energy Storage</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as a means of saving carbon emissions. The Government should also encourage all forms of Heat Recovery </span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">where this can be used in conjunction with thermal storage in order to save carbon emissions. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ICAX is a British c</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ompany that has proved its innovative technology, but DECC has not yet acknowledged that this major technical advance needs to be promoted by gover</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="color:#165e16; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ment.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>